This continued all the way up until after WWII, when kana was completely reformed to make spelling straightforward  So, if you pick up a book published in 1940, ã‚„ã£ã¦ã„ã‚‹ will be written as ã‚„ã¤ã¦ã‚ã‚‹ (but was pronounced the exact same as ã‚„ã£ã¦ã„ã‚‹)

Overtime, these sounds shifted and eventually became pronounced the same as ã„ and ãˆ. BUT, things that were ORIGINALLY pronounced as wi" and "we" continued to be written with ã‚ and ã‚‘  It's similar to how we still write "knife"
column12: even though we no longer pronounce the "k" sound"

tweet_content: Turns out it's more common for Japanese learners to not know about ã‚ and ã‚‘ at all!  Here's an explanation:  When kana was created ~1000 years ago, the sounds wi" and "we" were a common part of Japanese
column12: and they were written with ã‚ and ã‚‘ https://t.co/4hk3H47omo"

tweet_content: It's funny how many Japanese learners think that ã‚ is pronounced wi" and ã‚‘ "we"
column12: when in reality up until WWII both these characters were used constantly and were simply pronounced exactly the same as ã„ and ãˆ https://t.co/ulKNFnlqWG"

It would be interesting to see how various NFT marketplaces compete (not on liquidity) but on the ease of onboarding new users.   Do check out my article if you are keen to read more: https://t.co/elrDwTk1c6  Thank you for reading! âœ¨

What does this war show us?  ğŸ”¹Each NFT marketplace needs to decide what is their niche: what type of users they want on its platform.   ğŸ”¹No one is really too big to go up against in the Web3 space. We are early!   ğŸ”¹Users benefit either way because of friendly competition.

However, creating incentives that purely encourage volume is unwise as this will just result in wash trading (eg. LooksRare where an estimated $8b of wash trade is said to be generated making up the vast majority of its sales as users attempt to game the trading rewards model)

3âƒ£ Incentivize existing and new users  Anyone looking to build a product in the Web3 space has to build with a community first" mindset.   Different strategies need to be implemented for diff groups of users in order to command more usage and trading vol."

Factors such as allocation structure as well as a long-term strategy should be considered.   If the intention is to IPO, perhaps it does not make sense to create tokens as it will create more problems when it comes to regulations.

2âƒ£ Airdrop Tokens?  After $BLUR was airdropped to users, volume increased on BLUR as majority are attempting to bid for for S2.   However, simply creating tokens and giving them to users is not so straightforward. https://t.co/OF1YvAQD0g
